AB  - The integration of renewable energy sources (RES) into power systems can adversely affect system stability, particularly in cases of high RES penetration. However, system stability can be significantly improved by optimizing the parameters of key system components. This study aims to demonstrate this by analysing the dynamic response of a microgrid composed 100% RES under a three-phase short-circuit disturbance. Three scenarios are considered: (i) using default parameters for all components, (ii) optimizing only the control parameters of the battery energy storage system (BESS), and (iii) optimizing the control parameters of the BESS, photovoltaic (PV) units, and wind turbines (WTs). The particle swarm optimization (PSO) algorithm is employed to determine the optimal settings for each case. Simulation results provide a comprehensive insight into system behaviour, confirming that PSO-based parameter tuning effectively dampen power system oscillations and enhances overall system stability.
ER  - 

