Y1  - 9-12 Sept. 2025
AB  - Ocean wave prediction is vital in navigation, shipping planning, and marine engineering. Current wave prediction methods rely on real-time sensor data and apply artificial intelligence in wave level and energy forecasting. This paper presents a method to collect and preprocess wave image data on sea surface conditions to train a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) for real-time wave-level classification. In particular, a noise denoising technique based on Gaussian filtering, Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization (CLAHE), and input data augmentation ensures high-quality labeled image datasets to support deep learning models for marine navigation. The model is evaluated in a maritime simulation environment and on an actual ship controller, achieving over 90 % prediction accuracy with the proposed noise reduction techniques. The results are intended to be recommended to ship operators for implementation in both autopilot and hand control modes, enabling them to make more informed and timely decisions regarding vessel navigation. By integrating the prediction outputs with the control systems, ships can dynamically adjust their steering behavior based on real-time sea conditions, enhancing operational efficiency and safety.
ER  - 

