AB  - This paper presents the research and development of a predictive model for discharge voltage on high-voltage insulator surfaces, utilizing a hybrid architecture combining Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) and Artificial Neural Networks (ANN). Partial Discharge (PD) is identified as a critical factor in modern power systems that require extensive monitoring and automation, as it contributes to insulation degradation and compromises system reliability and operational safety. The research focuses on developing a deep learning model capable of extracting nonlinear features from both image-based inputs of surface contamination distribution and temperature and operating parameters such as voltage with the goal of accurately predicting the discharge voltage in real-time. The proposed model is trained on experimental data collected from a high-voltage discharge simulation platform under laboratory-controlled conditions, incorporating advanced signal processing techniques such as Gaussian noise filtering and Kalman Filtering. Experimental results demonstrate that the model achieves high performance in early detection and risk warning of partial discharge events, thereby enhancing grid reliability, reducing the likelihood of equipment failure, and optimizing predictive maintenance strategies within smart grid infrastructures.
ER  - 

