AB  - We investigate Tanner-graph-based signal detection of the large-scale multiple-input multiple-output (LS-MIMO)communication systems with low-resolution analog-to-digital converters (ADC) when higher-order modulation schemes such as amplitude shift keying (ASK) constellation is employed to attain high-bandwidth efficiency. The high-order modulation scheme combined with a large number of antennas imposes the complexity issue for the signal detector at the receiver end. This paper also performs the mathematical derivation to transform such a high-order superposition modulation channel model into the equivalent binary modulation channel model to exploit the advantages of the graph-based signal detection algorithm previously designed for the binary modulated scheme. Once the equivalent channel model is established, a framework to optimize 2L-ASK constellations for various MIMO configurations and resolution levels of the ADCs is developed. Our simulation results show that the constellations optimized for a specific resolution level of the ADCs outperform the conventional and equal-weight superposition constellations.
ER  - 

